         <div type="commentary">
            <head>Commentary</head>
            <p>Clearly from a composite base carrying statutes of the emperor Claudius and his family. Antonia, eldest daughter of Claudius, 
               survived until AD 65 A.D but the inscription in her honour is likely to belong to the reign of Claudius 41-54 A.D</p>
            <p>Letronne, followed by Franz (whence IGRR) took Pacho's drawing to represent a continuous text, with lacunae, and restored:
               1. <supplied reason="lost">Πτολεμαιέων ὁ δῆμος ὁ φιλοσ</supplied>έβασ<supplied reason="lost">τ</supplied>ος, 
               Κ<supplied reason="lost">λα</supplied>υ<supplied reason="lost">δίου Νέρωνος Δρούσου Γεργαμινικοῦ γυναικί (ἔτους)</supplied>
               2. Καίσαρο<supplied reason="lost">ς Φα</supplied>μ<supplied reason="lost">ενώθ</supplied></p>
            
            <p>Cf. BMC, Imp I, p.199 No. 242, a coin with Messalina Augusti on the obverse and Octavia, Britannicus and Antonia on the reverse; 
               see also the inscription IGGR IV.208.209 with Claudius and Agrippina and Octavia, Antonia and Britannicus (and Nero added later).</p>
         </div>
         
